  "prompt": "My boyfriend cheated on me. I felt betrayed and it still haunts me. How to stop thinking about it?",
  "response": "I'm so sorry you're going through this. Betrayal in a relationship can be incredibly painful, and it\u2019s natural for these thoughts to linger. While healing takes time, here are some steps that might help you process your emotions and move forward:\n\n### 1. **Acknowledge Your Feelings**\n   - It\u2019s okay to feel hurt, angry, or betrayed. Suppressing your emotions can make it harder to heal. Allow yourself to feel what you\u2019re feeling without judgment.\n\n### 2. **Talk to Someone You Trust**\n   - Sharing your feelings with a close friend, family member, or therapist can provide support and help you gain perspective. Sometimes, just verbalizing your thoughts can make them feel less overwhelming.\n\n### 3. **Decide What You Want**\n   - Reflect on whether you want to work through this with your boyfriend or move on. This decision is deeply personal and should be based on what feels right for you, not out of fear or obligation.\n\n### 4. **Set Boundaries**\n   - If you choose to stay in the relationship, establish clear boundaries and expectations with your boyfriend. If you decide to leave, focus on creating space to heal without contact.\n\n### 5. **Practice Self-Care**\n   - Take care of your physical and emotional well-being. Engage in activities that bring you joy, like exercise, hobbies, or spending time with loved ones.\n\n### 6. **Challenge Negative Thoughts**\n   - When thoughts about the betrayal arise, try to reframe them. For example, instead of thinking, \u201cI\u2019ll never trust anyone again,\u201d remind yourself, \u201cThis was a reflection of his actions, not my worth.\u201d\n\n### 7. **Focus on the Present**\n   - Mindfulness techniques, like deep breathing or meditation, can help you stay grounded in the present moment rather than dwelling on the past.\n\n### 8. **Give Yourself Time**\n   - Healing isn\u2019t linear, and it\u2019s okay to have moments of sadness or anger even after you feel like you\u2019ve moved on. Be patient with yourself.\n\n### 9. **Consider Professional Help**\n   - A therapist can provide tools to process your emotions, rebuild trust (whether in your current relationship or future ones), and develop healthy coping mechanisms.\n\n### 10. **Remember Your Worth**\n   - His actions do not define your value. You deserve love, respect, and honesty in a relationship.\n\nIf you\u2019re unsure about your next steps, take your time to think it through. It\u2019s important to prioritize your emotional well-being and make decisions that align with your needs and values. You\u2019re not alone, and with time and care, you can heal from this.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
